Exploring the Prosper Loan Dataset¶

by Gustaf Petersen¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

I have chosen the Prosper Loan Dataset, which is a financial dataset of borrowers and the many points of data collected regarding things such as:

  • risk assesments
  • credit ratings
  • interest rates
  • income ranges etc.

In fact, there are 81 columns with different variables where I have to explore what might be relevant and useful to analyse.

The company Prosper is a peer-to-peer funded lending service, helping borrowers lend from other peers instead of traditional banking, more info about prosper can be found here: https://www.prosper.com/about

Obviously, there are many variables that could be explored, but we will have to confine the number of variables to the exploration needed for the project. At least one of each: univariate, bivariate, and multivariate plots are required for the explanatory part, so we need a few more for the exploratory part for each in the exploratory part. The exploratory part is also needed to decide which plots and variables to showcase later. In order to help me figure out which variables to use for analysis I will use the 'Variable Definitions' sheet that came along with the dataset and figure out which variables to explore in the first case.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113'937 loans and 81 columns in the dataset. As a bank, or lender like Prosper, regardless of their differing models, require that their borrowers pay back their money with interest for the business model to be sound. Therefore, I want to find out which variables affect certain ratings for the borrowers and which variables could potentially help a company like prosper predict the beneficial traits for their lenders and provide financial security. Thus, the analysis will focus on finding out which variables can paint the best picture on which type or traits that borrowers posess in order to generate money according to their mission.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main interests here are investigating factors such as interest rates in comparison to credit scores to determine the relationships between what theoretically constitutes a good borrower then comparing those types what yields the best results for the lenders in the peer to peer loans. Are there any significant factors that correlates or shows any type of relation between the cost of a borrower exceeds the rewards.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think that the main feature of interest in the dataset is Borrower Rate, since the lenders, prosper and borrowers are all unified in the variable. Lenders need a high interest to be interested in getting a return for their lending, prosper needs to have a margin to host the service, borrowers need to get a reasonable rate in order to pay back the loan with a price that is reasonable and not ovewhelming. Thus the Investigation will focus on finding out where the different variables in the dataset might be indicative of how the Borrower Rate might increase or decrease.

The variables that I will examine are the following:

  • Credit Grade
  • Term
  • Borrower Rate
  • Estimated Loss
  • Estimated Return
  • Prosper Rating (numeric)
  • Prosper Rating (Alpha)
  • Prosper Score
  • Listing Category
  • Stated Monthly Income
  • Occupation
  • Listing Category
  • Occupation
  • EmploymentStatus
  • Employment Status Duration
  • Credit Score Range Lower
  • Credit Score Rang upper
  • Debt to Income Ratio
  • Income Range
  • Stated Monthly Income

# Listing Category (numeric) turn it into first strings from the numerical values.
# This is done by first creating a function containing 'if,elif,else' statements to evalueate which number in each row will be replaced
# by the corresponding category.
# Then by using lambda and apply method I can use my function on the column.
# This is a similar function as to the one I used on the previous project 

"""
List of corresponding Labels for all the numerical values:

 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business,
 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 
 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans,
 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle,
 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans
 
"""
# Creating a list with
listing_list = [
                'Not Available', 'Debt Consolidation', 'Home Improvement', 'Business', 'Personal Loan',
                'Student Use', 'Auto', 'Other', 'Baby&Adoption', 'Boat', 'Cosmetic Procedure',
                'Engagement Ring', 'Green Loans', 'Household Expenses', 'Large Purchases',
                'Medical/Dental', 'Motorcycle', 'RV', 'Taxes', 'Vacation', 'Wedding Loans'
               ]
# Creating a function that determines which number corresponds to the right category, and inserts the category
# into the column rows where they 'belong' from the list index of 'listing_list' 


def change_listing_cat(x):
    if x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 0:
        return listing_list[0]
    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 1:

    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 2:

    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 3:

        return listing_list[6]
    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 7:
        return listing_list[7]
    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 8:
        return listing_list[8]
    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 9:
        return listing_list[9]
    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 10:
        return listing_list[10]
    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 11:
        return listing_list[11]
    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 12:
        return listing_list[12]
    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 13:
        return listing_list[13]
    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 14:
        return listing_list[14]
    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 15:
        return listing_list[15]
    elif x['ListingCategory (numeric)'] == 16:
        return listing_list[16]

        return listing_list[17]

Results¶

I think that the biggest take away is that Estimated Loss may hugely affect which Prosper Rating a borrower recieves, which obviously then affects the Borrower Rate. Initially, I thought that the Estimated Return would have had the strongest correlation than it showed, but most surprising is the low effect of Stated Monthly Income on Borrower Rate. I assumed that the income would affect the rate more. Obviously there might have been more variables looked at, and from the 80 columns there could have been extensive research as to why and how variables relate to each other. It would have been interesting research more layers of qualitative and quantitative variables. However, I am satisfied that it seems Like Estimated Loss and Estimatet Return are key takeaways from my this gleer at Prospers Data.
